  <div class="lesson-content-memo"> Special Relativity  </div>   

A particle of matter in relativistic motion (relativistic speeds v ~ c) uses different formulae.
We will also assume that the particle is free.

The equations for a relativistic particle are:
<ul>
    <li>c = speed of light</li>
    <li>&#946 = v/c</li>
    <li>&#947;=1/Sqrt(1-&#946;<sup>2</sup>) </li>    
    <li> m<sub>0</sub> = rest mass </li>
    <li>m = &#947;m<sub>0</sub> = m<sub>0</sub> + (1/c<sup>2</sup>)&#189;mv<sup>2</sup> + ... </li>
    <li>mc<sup>2</sup> = m<sub>0</sub>c<sup>2</sup> +  KE </li>
    <li> KE = m<sub>0</sub>c<sup>2</sup>(&#947;-1) </li>  
</ul>
    Particle momentum p is also related to rest mass and total energy by: 
    E<sup>2</sup> = p<sup>2</sup>c<sup>2</sup> + m<sub>0</sub><sup>2</sup>c<sup>4</sup>.

